<PageLayout
  title="Constitutional Non-Alignment for a Multipolar Era"
  description="South Africa's grand strategy — analysis, critique, and realignment — and how the GovCompass Reform Agenda provides the domestic execution layer on which it depends."
>
  <!-- Hero -->
  <header class="mb-10">
    <p class="font-heading text-sm font-semibold text-compass-green uppercase tracking-wide mb-2">
      Topic — Grand Strategy
    </p>
    <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-3 leading-tight">
      Constitutional Non-Alignment for a Multipolar Era
    </h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
      South Africa's grand strategy — analysis, critique, and realignment — and how the GovCompass
      Reform Agenda provides the domestic execution layer on which it depends.
    </p>
    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-6">
      This is the synthesis article for the Topics section. It reconstructs South Africa's grand strategy from
      its doctrinal stack, evaluates it through the classical Ends–Ways–Means triad, and proposes an
      endowment-aligned alternative. It then shows, explicitly, how every pillar of the GovCompass Reform
      Agenda maps to a component of that grand strategy — so that readers who have worked through the five
      Topic pillars can see exactly how domestic reform plugs into national strategic ambition.
    </p>

    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-sm text-text-secondary font-heading border-t border-gray-200 pt-4">
      <span>Citizen X</span>
      <time datetime={publishDate.toISOString()}>{formattedDate}</time>
      <span aria-label={`${readingTime} minute read`}>{readingTime} min read</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <JumpToSection links={jumpLinks} class="mb-12" />

  <!-- Section 1: Introduction & Conceptual Foundation -->
  <section id="introduction" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Introduction and conceptual foundation">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 1</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      What Grand Strategy Is and Why It Matters for South Africa
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Grand strategy is the highest level of statecraft. It is the discipline by which a nation
      coordinates every instrument of power it possesses — military, economic, diplomatic, technological,
      cultural, informational — to secure its core interests over decades. Where military strategy asks
      "how do we win this war?", grand strategy asks a prior and larger question: "what kind of world do
      we want to live in, and how do we arrange the full weight of the state to help produce it?" The
      two questions are related but not the same. A state can win every battle and still lose its
      strategic position, because victory on the battlefield does not by itself answer the question of
      whether the state's ends, ways, and means are in durable alignment.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The intellectual lineage of grand strategy runs from Liddell Hart's insistence that strategy
      extends beyond the battlefield into the peace that follows, through Paul Kennedy's thesis that
      great powers decline when strategic commitments outrun their economic base, to Luttwak's
      reconstruction of Roman grand strategy as a system that evolved with circumstance rather than a
      fixed doctrine. John Lewis Gaddis distilled the practical test — grand strategy is the calculated
      relationship of means to large ends — and Colin Gray reminded readers that grand strategy is the
      direction and use made of any and all of the assets of a security community for the political
      purposes that community has adopted. Across the tradition, the unifying insight is disciplinary:
      grand strategy is what happens when a state refuses to treat its military, economic, diplomatic,
      and domestic choices as separate conversations and instead asks how they add up.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Why this matters for South Africa, right now, is a question with a specific answer. South Africa
      is an upper-middle-income economy that is deindustrialising. It is trapped between the strategic
      ambitions of a developed state — universal welfare provision, complex industry, global diplomatic
      weight, G20-level convening — and the fiscal and institutional base of a struggling emerging
      market. Unemployment sits above 32 per cent, the narrow definition; broader measures climb past
      40 per cent. Core infrastructure has decayed: the electricity grid, the ports and rail, the
      water treatment works, the roads network. A newly published National Security Strategy, released
      to the public on 15 July 2025, declares eight security pillars. A Framework Document on the
      National Interest, adopted by Cabinet in 2022, names four core national interests. A pending
      Long-Term Force Evolution Strategy — "Journey to Greatness" — proposes a 1.5 per cent of GDP
      defence floor. Yet the economic base on which every one of these commitments rests is producing
      growth rates that, by the Reserve Bank's own projections, will keep per-capita income stagnant
      for the remainder of the decade.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A country that takes its grand strategy seriously has to confront the arithmetic. A country that
      does not ends up with a doctrinal stack that describes a world the state cannot afford, a defence
      force it cannot fund, and a diplomatic posture whose costs it cannot absorb. The analysis that
      follows is an attempt to bring the doctrinal ambition and the economic arithmetic into the same
      conversation — not to diminish the former, but to specify what it would take to fund it.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The architecture of this piece proceeds in four moves. The first reconstructs South Africa's
      actual grand strategy from the doctrinal stack — the constitutional, strategic, foreign-policy,
      defence, and development tiers that together constitute the country's answer to the grand-strategic
      question, even though no single document carries the title. The second evaluates that strategy
      through the classical Ends–Ways–Means triad, through four interpretive lenses, and through a risk
      register that names the six most visible gaps between doctrine and delivery. The third proposes
      an endowment-aligned alternative — a grand strategy designed from South Africa's actual resource
      base rather than inherited from doctrinal inertia. The fourth makes the bridging argument: how
      the existing strategy and the proposed alternative connect, and — crucially for the readers of
      GovCompass — how the Reform Agenda articulated across this site is the domestic execution layer
      without which either strategy remains performative.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The tone throughout is analytical rather than advocatory. The goal is not to persuade a reader
      toward any particular political position, but to give a reader the conceptual apparatus to judge
      for themselves whether the country's strategic commitments and its economic base are in
      alignment — and, if they are not, what realignment would require. Grand strategy belongs to
      citizens as much as to cabinets. The citizens who understand it are the ones who can hold the
      cabinet to it.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: Doctrinal Stack -->
  <section id="doctrinal-stack" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="The doctrinal stack">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 2</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      Reconstructing the Grand Strategy from Its Doctrinal Architecture
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa does not publish a single document titled "Grand Strategy." The phrase appears in
      academic commentary and in think-tank analysis, but no statutory instrument, presidential
      proclamation, or white paper gathers the ambition under that heading. This absence is not an
      oversight; it is a feature of how the state has chosen to articulate its strategic purpose. The
      grand strategy must instead be reconstructed from a layered doctrinal stack, each layer operating
      at a different altitude, each layer binding on the layers below it.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The constitutional tier sits at the top. The Constitution of 1996 — especially Section 198, which
      opens the chapter on security services — defines security as inseparable from human dignity,
      equality, and freedom. "National security must reflect the resolve of South Africans, as
      individuals and as a nation, to live as equals, to live in peace and harmony, to be free from
      fear and want and to seek a better life." This formulation is not decorative. It binds every
      downstream strategic document to a values-first definition of security, one that treats
      developmental outcomes — not only territorial defence — as constitutive of national security
      itself. Few states' grand strategies are anchored this deep in constitutional values. South
      Africa's is.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Below the constitutional tier sits the strategic tier. The National Security Strategy
      2024–2029, publicly released on 15 July 2025, is the central document here. Its release marked
      the first transparent publication of core intelligence doctrine in South African history — a
      posture shift from the classified tradition inherited from the State Security Agency era. The
      NSS articulates eight security pillars, maps a threat landscape, and situates security within
      the developmental mandate of the state. Alongside the NSS sit the National Intelligence
      Estimate for the 2019–2024 period, which inventoried threats to the economy, territorial
      integrity, state authority, citizen well-being, and the global environment, and the National
      Intelligence Priorities that cascade downward to operational intelligence tasking.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The foreign-policy tier articulates how the state operates externally. The 2011 White Paper
      "Building a Better World: The Diplomacy of Ubuntu" remains the principal articulation of
      diplomatic philosophy — humanity in connection, peaceful conflict resolution, Global South
      solidarity. The DIRCO Strategic Plan 2025–2030 translates that philosophy into a programme of
      activity: economic diplomacy, multilateral positioning, consular services, and development
      cooperation through SADPA. The 2022 Framework Document on the National Interest, adopted by
      Cabinet in the wake of academic and policy debate over how South Africa defines its own
      interests, names four — Survival, Prosperity, Identity, and Influence — and provides the
      conceptual hinge between foreign-policy philosophy and security doctrine.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The defence tier specifies how force is organised and used. The 1996 White Paper on Defence
      established the post-1994 normative framework; the 1998 and 2015 Defence Reviews updated force
      design and capability planning; and the pending Long-Term Force Evolution Strategy 2025–2055,
      known by its internal title "Journey to Greatness," proposes a multi-decade trajectory toward a
      defence expenditure floor of 1.5 per cent of GDP. As of late 2025 the Strategy still awaits a
      Special National Security Council session before adoption — a delay that itself is doctrinally
      informative, in that the force-evolution layer remains suspended while the fiscal and political
      conditions for its adoption are negotiated.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The development tier anchors the domestic limb of the grand strategy. The National Development
      Plan — Vision 2030, adopted in 2012 — remains the reference framework for every department's
      planning cycle, even as its 2030 target date approaches without the growth and employment
      outcomes it promised. The NDP is the explicit bridge between the foreign-policy vision of "a
      better South Africa, in a better Africa, in a better world" and the domestic machinery that is
      supposed to deliver it.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Why the stacked-doctrine approach matters analytically is that it forces the analyst to read
      coherence vertically rather than horizontally. The question is not whether any one layer is
      internally sound, but whether the layers point in the same direction. A NSS that names economic
      security as a pillar and a NDP that has not produced economic security are in vertical tension.
      A White Paper on Foreign Policy that invokes Ubuntu values and a BRICS partnership that includes
      authoritarian states under investigation by the International Criminal Court are in vertical
      tension. Vertical tension is not a failure; it is the material from which grand strategy is
      negotiated. But it must be named.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The doctrinal stack is not read in isolation. A substantial think-tank overlay provides
      independent scrutiny — the Institute for Security Studies, the South African Institute of
      International Affairs, the Brenthurst Foundation's archive of developmental-state analysis, the
      Belfer Center's work on middle-power positioning, and the academic journals (the South African
      Journal of International Affairs, African Security Review, Strategic Review for Southern
      Africa) that provide the peer-reviewed counterweight to government doctrine. The reader who
      wants to understand South Africa's grand strategy has to read both the stack and the overlay.
      The sections that follow do so.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 3: Ends -->
  <section id="ends" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="The ends of grand strategy">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 3</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      The Ends: What South Africa Seeks to Achieve
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Ends of South Africa's grand strategy are articulated at three nested levels. At the widest
      level sits the overarching vision: "A better South Africa, in a better Africa, in a better
      world." The phrase recurs, almost verbatim, in the 2011 White Paper on Foreign Policy, the
      National Development Plan, the DIRCO Strategic Plan 2025–2030, and the National Security
      Strategy. Its repetition is not rhetorical filler. It encodes a specific doctrinal choice:
      domestic transformation, continental renewal, and the reform of the global order are treated
      as one integrated programme rather than three separable objectives. The constitutional values
      that bind domestic policy — dignity, equality, non-racialism, the primacy of the rule of law —
      are the same values that are projected into the African agenda and into the multilateral reform
      agenda. The vision is, in its own terms, constitutionally rooted and values-driven.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The middle level specifies the four core national interests, codified in the 2022 Framework
      Document on the National Interest and echoed through the NSS. Survival covers sovereignty,
      territorial integrity, and the protection of the constitutional order — the preconditions
      without which no other interest can be pursued. Prosperity covers growth, employment, the
      reduction of poverty and inequality, and the productive base from which the state draws its
      resources; it is the domestic economic content of the national interest, usually condensed in
      political discourse into the phrase "the triple challenge" of poverty, inequality, and
      unemployment. Identity covers the constitutional values, social cohesion, and the Ubuntu
      tradition that the state treats as its normative signature. Influence covers the voice of South
      Africa — and, more broadly, of Africa and the Global South — in the forums that shape global
      rules. The four interests are presented as coequal; in practice, as later sections will show,
      they are not.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The narrowest level is the NSS's eight security pillars, which operationalise the Ends across
      mutually exclusive security domains. Each pillar names a field of operational activity and
      carries downstream planning obligations.
    </p>

    <div class="grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-3 mb-6">
      {nssPillars.map((p) => (
        <div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <div class="flex items-baseline gap-2 mb-1">
            <span class="font-heading text-xs font-bold text-compass-green">Pillar {p.n}</span>
            <span class="font-heading text-sm font-semibold text-text-primary">{p.title}</span>
          </div>
          <p class="text-xs text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">{p.desc}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The pillars are structured to be MECE. Public Security is the protection of persons and
      communities from crime and disorder; Territorial Integrity is the protection of borders, airspace,
      and the exclusive economic zone; Sovereignty Projection is the credible capacity to defend the
      constitutional order and project influence externally; Economic Security is the productive base
      on which every other pillar rests; Cyber and Information Security is the defence of digital and
      informational infrastructure; Technology and Innovation is the indigenous capability in strategic
      technologies; Environmental and Natural Resource Security is water, food, energy, and climate
      resilience treated as security concerns; Cultural Security is social cohesion and the identity
      dimension of nation-building.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The "negative" of the Ends is supplied by the National Intelligence Estimate's five threat axes:
      threats to the economy, to territorial integrity, to state authority, to citizen well-being, and
      threats emanating from the global environment. The inverse mapping is deliberate. If Economic
      Security is a pillar, then threats to the economy — grey-listing, tariff retaliation, state
      capture of fiscal institutions — are counted as security threats, not merely as economic news.
      If Sovereignty Projection is a pillar, then threats to state authority — organised criminal
      networks, illicit financial flows, the collapse of the criminal-justice pipeline — are counted
      as strategic rather than departmental. The inversion is the bridge by which the Estimate
      translates into intelligence tasking.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Are the Ends internally coherent? At the level of stated ambition, broadly yes. The vision is
      clear, the four interests are well-specified, and the eight pillars are domain-complete. The
      values framework does real work — the Rome Statute obligations, the commitment to international
      humanitarian law, the Ubuntu tradition — in a way that differentiates South Africa from
      non-aligned peers whose strategic doctrine is more transactional.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      Are the Ends realistic, given the state's current economic position? That is a different
      question, and it is where the doctrinal stack encounters the arithmetic. A state with a
      ~$400 billion GDP, a narrow tax base, a declining per-capita income, and a military budget 43
      per cent below its own stated baseline cannot simultaneously deliver all eight pillars at the
      level the NSS implies. The Ends are aspirational in the literal sense: they describe what the
      state seeks, not what it has yet built the base to afford. The later sections — on Means, on
      Risks, and on the endowment-aligned alternative — take up the implications of that gap.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 4: Ways -->
  <section id="ways" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Strategic posture and ways">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 4</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      The Ways: Converting Interests into Action
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Four distinctive Ways define South Africa's strategic posture. They are analytically separable
      but operationally interlinked, and each has a body of doctrinal and academic literature clarifying
      its scope. Together they form the repertoire by which the state attempts to convert its stated
      interests into external action.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      1. Active Non-Alignment and Strategic Autonomy
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Active non-alignment is not neutrality. It is the deliberate refusal of bloc allegiance combined
      with active coalition-building across blocs. Minister of International Relations Ronald Lamola's
      September 2025 articulation — that South Africa's foreign policy is governed by principle rather
      than camp, and that the country retains the right to vote its conscience in every multilateral
      forum — is the most recent authoritative statement of the doctrine. The Hague Group
      co-chairmanship, the ICJ case against Israel, and the measured handling of Ukraine are the
      proof-points most often cited. The academic literature, particularly the work of Otto and Nagar
      in the South African Journal of International Affairs, has refined the concept further as
      "negotiated institutional accommodation" — a posture sustained through flexible legal
      interpretation rather than open defiance of international norms, as illustrated by the 2023 BRICS
      summit's handling of the Putin arrest-warrant dilemma, where the state resolved a constitutional
      conflict through a procedural mechanism rather than a political confrontation.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      2. Pan-African Agency and the Regional Anchor Role
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Africa is doctrinally "the centre" of South African foreign and security policy. The 2011 White
      Paper, the NSS, and the DIRCO Strategic Plan all position Pan-African agency as the first-order
      Way. Operational expressions are numerous: SADC and AU Standby Force support; the SAMIDRC
      deployment in the eastern Democratic Republic of Congo; the championing of the African
      Continental Free Trade Area; the long-running push for a permanent African seat on the United
      Nations Security Council; the projection of peace-mediation credentials from Lesotho and
      Burundi in the past to Sudan and the Great Lakes in the present. The Way asserts that South
      Africa cannot be a credible global actor if it is not first a credible regional actor, and that
      continental integration is both a developmental and a security project.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      3. Ubuntu Diplomacy and Values-Based Norm Entrepreneurship
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The 2011 White Paper's diplomatic signature is Ubuntu — humanity-as-interconnection — translated
      into peaceful conflict resolution, Global South solidarity, and normative positioning in
      multilateral forums. South Africa projects itself as a norm entrepreneur: the state that takes
      the Palestinian cause to the ICJ, the state that carries the decolonial agenda into the G20,
      the state whose Constitutional Court judgments on dignity and equality are cited in foreign
      jurisdictions. The critique, articulated most sharply by Brooks Spector through SAIIA
      commentary and echoed by the ISS, is that the posture is normatively aspirational but
      operationally thin: the values rhetoric is not matched by a commensurate delivery apparatus,
      and the state's own domestic record on human-rights indicators complicates the external
      projection.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      4. Multi-Aligned Multilateralism
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The fourth Way is the deliberate stacking of memberships. BRICS, the G20, IBSA, the Non-Aligned
      Movement, the Commonwealth, the African Union, the Southern African Development Community, the
      European Union Strategic Partnership, the rotating UN Security Council seat — the state holds a
      portfolio of memberships unmatched by any other middle power. The portfolio is used to leverage
      every forum for Global South agenda-setting while maintaining Western market access. The
      Belfer Center has characterised this in a November 2025 analysis as "coordinated
      multi-alignment" — not a confusion of affiliations but a calculated attempt to extract
      informational and bargaining advantage from each forum simultaneously.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Are the Four Ways Consistent?
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The four Ways are not obviously contradictory, but they generate real tensions that the state
      has to manage in real time. Active non-alignment and Ubuntu values constrain behaviour in BRICS
      forums where partners do not share the values. Pan-African agency and multi-aligned
      multilateralism compete for finite diplomatic attention and budget. Norm entrepreneurship on
      the Palestinian question sits beside relative silence on Sudan and parts of the Sahel — an
      inconsistency SAIIA has named directly. The 2023 Putin–ICC episode is the illustrative case:
      the state simultaneously maintained BRICS solidarity (Way 4), honoured its Rome Statute
      obligations (Way 3), preserved Pan-African standing (Way 2), and refused bloc pressure from
      both sides (Way 1) — through a procedural accommodation that, while legally workable, drew
      criticism from every constituency at once.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The honest reading is that the four Ways are simultaneously operable only when the state has
      sufficient diplomatic, economic, and military depth to absorb the tensions they generate. As
      the economic base narrows and the military instrument degrades, the bandwidth for managing
      contradiction narrows with it. The Ways do not then fail; they become more expensive to
      sustain, and the trade-offs that were previously invisible become visible. Section 7 returns
      to this dynamic under the heading of Risks.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 5: Means -->
  <section id="means" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="The instruments of national power">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 5</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      The Means: Instruments of National Power — A DIME Assessment
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The DIME framework — Diplomatic, Informational, Military, Economic — is the standard analytic
      grid for assessing the instruments of national power. Applied to South Africa it produces a
      portrait whose unevenness is itself the most important finding. The state is diplomatically
      overweight and militarily and economically hollow, and the mismatch between the instruments
      defines the strategic problem.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Diplomatic
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa maintains approximately 120 diplomatic missions abroad — one of the larger
      footprints in the Global South. The DIRCO Strategic Plan 2025–2030 centralises economic
      diplomacy as a principal function, shifting missions from representational toward outcome-based
      commercial roles. The state holds a membership portfolio unmatched by its peers: BRICS, G20,
      IBSA, NAM, Commonwealth, AU, SADC, EU Strategic Partnership, and rotational UN Security Council
      seats. It has exercised convening power at scale — the 2023 BRICS summit, the 2025 G20
      presidency, the 2025 SA–EU summit — and maintains SADPA as a development-assistance channel.
      The diplomatic instrument is the most capable arm of national power, and its capability is the
      principal source of the state's outsized strategic profile relative to its economic weight.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Informational
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The informational instrument is mixed. On the asset side, the Ubuntu narrative functions as
      soft power, the G20 messaging on an equitable international order has landed, and the NSS's
      own publication was itself a transparency-as-soft-power move. On the weakness side, NSS Pillar 5
      — Cyber and Information Security — is explicitly flagged by the state as under-developed. The
      country's counter-disinformation capability is limited, information-space sovereignty is weak,
      and cybersecurity posture lags the threat profile. The gap is not for want of awareness; it is
      for want of investment and coordinated architecture.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Military
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The South African National Defence Force is the most degraded instrument in the portfolio, and
      the structural numbers are stark. The baseline budget requirement, as estimated by the Department
      of Defence itself, is approximately R98.3 billion; the 2025–26 allocation is R57.2 billion — a
      structural deficit of 43 per cent. More than 60 per cent of that constrained allocation is
      consumed by personnel costs, leaving operational and capital budgets residual. Force-structure
      data tell the same story. Of 26 Gripen fighters on the books, roughly 12 are reported
      operational. The C-130BZ transport fleet, the backbone of strategic airlift, is largely not
      airworthy. The submarine arm is non-functional. The frigate force has, by public accounts, one
      operational vessel at any given time.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Operational consequences followed in early 2025 when the SAMIDRC deployment suffered the loss
      of 14 SANDF soldiers in the eastern DRC — an engagement that exposed deficits in air cover,
      intelligence-surveillance-reconnaissance, and medical-evacuation capacity. The governance
      collapse of Denel, the state defence-industrial prime, has removed domestic production of
      several systems the SANDF depends on. The 2015 Defence Review had set a force-design trajectory
      oriented around Special Operations and a Medium Combat Forces capability; current funding
      supports neither. The pending Long-Term Force Evolution Strategy 2025–2055 targets a 1.5 per
      cent of GDP defence floor that Minister Motshekga has publicly conceded will take "many years"
      to reach. The instrument, in short, is insufficient for the Sovereignty Projection pillar the
      NSS claims.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Economic
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The economic instrument presents the largest portfolio of latent strengths and active
      vulnerabilities. Strengths: two-ocean geography astride the Cape route, the world's deepest
      reserves of platinum-group metals, manganese, and chromium, deep capital markets and a
      sophisticated financial and legal services sector, and a bilateral BRICS trade relationship
      estimated at roughly $50 billion in 2022. The Department of Trade, Industry and Competition's
      economic-diplomacy mechanism and DIRCO's 2025–2030 reorientation together constitute a
      commercial-diplomacy architecture that, on paper, is credible.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Vulnerabilities: the Financial Action Task Force grey-listing imposed reputational and
      operational costs on cross-border finance; the United States' 30 per cent reciprocal tariff
      imposed in August 2025 removed a material share of the export advantage to the US market; the
      AGOA review creates further uncertainty; state-owned enterprise decay — Eskom, Transnet, and
      the water boards — continues to degrade the network-industry base on which private investment
      depends. The economic instrument is potentially formidable; it is actually under-performing.
      The gap between potential and performance is the most consequential DIME finding, because it
      is the gap that funds — or fails to fund — every other instrument.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The DIME Judgement
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The portfolio is diplomatically overweight and militarily and economically hollow. That is the
      clear judgement. The diplomatic instrument is used, successfully, to extract strategic position
      that the economic and military instruments cannot earn. This extraction has limits. When the
      underlying base does not grow, the diplomatic premium erodes, and external actors price the
      mismatch — in tariff policy, in investment decisions, in the terms of bilateral deals — more
      sharply than they did a decade ago. The strategic task is not to trim the diplomatic instrument
      but to rebuild the economic base that gives it durable leverage.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 6: Perspectives -->
  <section id="perspectives" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Four interpretive perspectives">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 6</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      Four Lenses: How Different Constituencies Read the Strategy
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      No grand-strategic analysis is the analyst's alone. Four interpretive camps read South Africa's
      grand strategy, and the camps are mutually exclusive enough that distinguishing them is a
      precondition for thinking clearly about the doctrinal stack. This section presents each fairly
      and allows the reader to weigh them.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Official Government Reading
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The NSS and DIRCO frame grand strategy as people-centred human security fused with active
      non-alignment. Minister of State Security Khumbudzo Ntshavheni cast the July 2025 release of
      the NSS as "democratic renewal" and as the culmination of a post-State-Capture transparency
      turn. The success metrics, as the government states them, are fidelity to the constitutional
      values framework, African agency in continental institutions, reform of the multilateral
      architecture to admit Global South voice, and domestic progress against the triple challenge.
      The official reading treats the doctrinal stack as internally coherent and treats delivery gaps
      as a problem of implementation rather than of doctrine.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Independent Think-Tank Mainstream
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Institute for Security Studies and the South African Institute of International Affairs
      together articulate the mainstream independent reading. Jakkie Cilliers's African Futures work
      at the ISS has argued that the architecture of the strategy is sound but undermined, first,
      by foreign-policy drift toward Russia that is not in the national interest; second, by DIRCO
      capacity decay that erodes the diplomatic instrument's effectiveness; and, third, by the
      failure to convert values-based positioning into tangible economic benefit — trade, investment,
      and growth. Foreign policy, on this reading, should be measured by commercial outcomes.
      Elizabeth Sidiropoulos and her colleagues at SAIIA, writing particularly on the G20 presidency,
      have argued that the strategy is coherent on norm entrepreneurship but suffers from
      inconsistency in application — moral rhetoric on Gaza that outpaces equivalent action on Sudan
      and the Sahel — and that the Global South's numerical majority in multilateral forums can only
      be converted into agenda-setting power through technical expertise and sustained working-group
      engagement, neither of which the state currently supplies at scale.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Contrarian and Reformist Reading
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A distinct body of analysis — Greg Mills and Ray Hartley through the Brenthurst Foundation
      archive, the Belfer Center on middle-power positioning, and the opposition analytical traditions
      associated with the Democratic Alliance and Free SA — reads the grand-strategic problem as
      fundamentally economic. On this reading, without sustained growth in the five-per-cent range,
      all strategic ambition becomes unfunded rhetoric. Brenthurst's "Asian Aspiration" thesis urges
      emulation of East Asian developmental-state discipline — export orientation, skills
      formation, fiscal conservatism, and sustained political will behind productive sectors. The
      Belfer Center's November 2025 analysis placed South Africa in the ambitious-Global-South
      agenda-setter camp but concluded that the China-leaning tilt in non-alignment has generated
      costly retaliation, particularly from the United States. The DA's critique, presented during
      parliamentary debate on the NSS, characterises the document as ambitious on paper, under-
      resourced in practice, and vague on the trade-offs between competing pillars.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      The Military and Defence-Community Reading
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      defenceWeb, the Stellenbosch Centre for Military Studies, and the Africa Center for Strategic
      Studies together articulate the defence-community reading. The consensus is that the NSS
      correctly identifies defence as a pillar but that the SANDF as currently resourced cannot
      execute the pillar. Moses Khanyile and his colleagues have highlighted the intelligence-
      surveillance-reconnaissance and early-warning gaps exposed by SAMIDRC. The Africa Center, in
      its 2019 analysis of the old classified NSS, argued that the secrecy itself prevented coherent
      cross-departmental use of the Strategy; the 2025 publication partially remedies this, but the
      remedy is informational and does not itself close the capability gap. The reading insists that
      doctrinal aspiration without force-structure investment is not strategy.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The four lenses do not converge on a single verdict; they converge on a single observation.
      The strategy's architecture is at most broadly coherent; its delivery is at best uneven; and
      the binding constraint across all four readings is the same — the economic base. Where the
      readings differ is on what weight to give the diplomatic achievements of the doctrine relative
      to the delivery gap at home. The next section names the delivery gap in six families.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 7: Risks -->
  <section id="risks" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Risks and implementation gaps">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 7</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      The Delta Between Doctrine and Delivery: Six Failure Modes
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The gap between stated strategy and observable execution resolves into six risk families. They
      are mutually exclusive enough to be diagnosed separately and collectively exhaustive enough to
      map the full delivery shortfall.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Ends–Means Mismatch.</strong> The NSS asserts military power
      as a pillar, yet the SANDF budget supports border patrol and limited peacekeeping — not the
      regional anchor-state projection that Pillar 3 implies. The Sovereignty Projection pillar is the
      clearest case of an End without corresponding Means. Closing the gap requires either a
      substantial uplift in the defence budget or a frank revision of the pillar toward what the
      force can actually do.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Values–Interests Tension.</strong> The ICJ Gaza case, the
      BRICS naval exercises alongside Russia and China, and the 2023 Putin–ICC episode illustrate the
      tension between the constitutional values framework and the partnership portfolio. Otto and
      Nagar's scenario analysis rates "Idealism under Strain" as the most probable trajectory —
      values-based positioning persists but is incrementally adapted to the cost of partnership
      maintenance. The tension is not resolvable by doctrine alone; it is managed, episode by
      episode, through the procedural and legal interpretation of each case.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Coordination Deficits.</strong> The 2018 High-Level Review
      Panel on the State Security Agency documented policy incoherence at the heart of the security
      community. The National Security Council was effectively moribund before President Ramaphosa's
      2019 revival, and the NICOC, NSS Secretariat, and NSC still face questions about capacity and
      decision-making cadence. The coordination problem is a binding constraint on every other
      pillar, because without a functioning coordination spine, the pillars are administered
      separately and the doctrinal coherence the NSS asserts is not produced operationally.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Economic Foundation Risk.</strong> Grey-listing, stagnant
      growth, Eskom and Transnet dysfunction, unemployment above 32 per cent, and capital outflows
      together erode the fiscal base on which every NSS pillar depends. This is the critique shared
      across every think-tank camp: official, mainstream, contrarian, and defence-community. The
      consensus is analytically rare and politically significant. Without growth, the other risks
      compound; with growth, several resolve themselves.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">External Coercion Risk.</strong> The United States' 30 per
      cent reciprocal tariff imposed in August 2025, the AGOA non-renewal threat, and the Trump
      administration's bilateral review together mark a shift in the cost profile of non-alignment.
      Non-alignment has always carried costs; it is becoming materially more expensive. External
      actors are now pricing the China-leaning tilt, and the economic instrument has to absorb the
      cost — which, given its current condition, it cannot easily do.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Regional Blowback Risk.</strong> Mozambique's Cabo Delgado
      insurgency, the M23 conflict in eastern DRC, and SADC fragmentation expose South Africa to
      spillover risks — terrorism, illicit arms, cross-border migration, criminal networks — that
      current SANDF capability cannot address and that current regional architecture cannot
      coordinate. The Pan-African Way cannot be sustained at the level of ambition the doctrine
      asserts without either a regional-defence capacity the country does not have or a regional
      institutional machinery the continent has not built.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The six risks compound each other in a specific order. Economic weakness starves the military,
      which undermines regional credibility, which reduces diplomatic leverage, which makes external
      coercion more effective, which further narrows the economic base. The loop runs backward. Any
      credible strategy for realignment has to break the loop at the economic node — because that
      is the node whose recovery most rapidly eases the others. The next section proposes what such
      a realignment looks like.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 8: Alternative -->
  <section id="alternative" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Endowment-aligned alternative">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 8</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      Playing the Hand South Africa Actually Holds
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      A grand strategy aligned to South Africa's actual endowments looks different from one inherited
      from doctrinal inertia. It is built upward from the resource base rather than downward from
      doctrinal ambition. The discipline is to ask, first, what the country actually holds, and,
      second, what strategy makes the best use of that hand over the fifteen-to-twenty-year window
      during which the demographic dividend remains open.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The endowment stack is well-defined. South Africa holds world-leading reserves of
      platinum-group metals, manganese, chromium, and vanadium — the precise inputs for electric-
      vehicle drivetrains, green-hydrogen production, grid-scale battery storage, and high-grade
      stainless steel. The country has the deepest capital markets and most sophisticated financial
      and legal services sector in Africa. Its two-ocean geography astride the Cape route makes it
      the natural logistics gateway to the SADC interior. Its population is young — the demographic
      dividend remains open for roughly fifteen to twenty years — though it is skills-mismatched in
      ways that the education and TVET systems have not closed. Residual but decayed industrial,
      rail, and port infrastructure provides a base from which reconstruction is feasible, not a
      starting point from scratch. Diplomatic credibility as a non-aligned middle power and BRICS
      member remains a genuine, if declining, asset. Taken together, the endowment stack suggests a
      specific strategic programme.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Five mutually reinforcing pillars follow from the endowment analysis.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar A — Mineral-Led Green Industrialisation
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Indonesia-nickel and Chile-lithium playbooks offer a credible template. Both countries tied
      their raw-material export regimes to mandatory domestic beneficiation — refining, smelting,
      and higher-value-chain activity onshore — in exchange for continued access to international
      markets. South Africa can pursue the equivalent strategy for PGM fuel cells, manganese cathode
      materials, and vanadium flow batteries. This is the one sector where the country's endowments
      match twenty-first-century demand precisely, and the strategic value of the mineral base
      depreciates if it is captured only as raw-material rent. Green industrialisation is not an
      environmental preference; it is the fiscal foundation of the next twenty years.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar B — Energy Transition as Industrial Policy
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Eskom crisis is the binding constraint on the entire endowment-aligned programme — and it
      is an opportunity, not only a liability. A credible energy-transition programme builds domestic
      solar, wind, and green-hydrogen manufacturing capability, co-locates production with PGM
      deposits to compress the supply chain, and treats decarbonisation as the vehicle for
      reindustrialisation. The REIPPPP procurement framework provides a starting architecture; the
      Just Energy Transition Partnership provides a financing channel. The strategic question is
      whether the country uses the transition to build industry or merely to import green technology
      from manufacturers elsewhere. The answer determines whether the energy sector becomes a growth
      engine or a cost centre.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar C — Regional Anchor Strategy
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      South Africa cannot compete head-on with Asian manufacturing at scale. It can be the financial,
      logistics, and industrial hub of the AfCFTA — Johannesburg as Africa's capital market, Durban
      and Ngqura as container gateways, the rail corridor as the connective tissue of SADC trade.
      The comparative advantage is institutional depth and geographic position, not labour cost.
      The regional anchor strategy is the domestic expression of the Pan-African Way: continental
      integration is both developmental and security-positive because it enlarges the market for
      South African output and reduces the exposure of SADC economies to extra-regional shocks.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar D — State Capacity Reconstruction Before Expansion
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The developmental-state agenda cannot be advanced through an expansion of the state's scope
      while the existing scope is under-performing. The endowment-aligned strategy requires a
      deliberate sequencing: capacity first, expansion second. That means ruthless civil-service
      professionalisation, the unbundling and reform of Eskom and Transnet, the repair of the
      revenue authority and the prosecutorial apparatus, and the insulation of technical appointments
      from political interference. Fiscal consolidation is part of the same package, as are targeted
      cash transfers rather than a universal Basic Income Grant — the tax base cannot support Nordic
      ambitions, and pretending otherwise produces deficit-financed promises that the next generation
      cannot honour.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Pillar E — Strategic Non-Alignment as Leverage
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Non-alignment, properly understood, is not an identity but a tool. It is valuable to the extent
      that it generates bargaining leverage with the United States and the European Union (market
      access, AGOA-type deals, capital), with China (infrastructure financing, industrial capacity,
      technology transfer), and with BRICS partners (diplomatic weight in forums that exclude the
      West). The endowment-aligned Way uses non-alignment to extract concessions from all three,
      without picking sides publicly, and reserves its values-based positioning for cases where the
      constitutional framework requires it. This is not a retreat from the 2011 White Paper; it is
      a disciplining of its application.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      What to Give Up
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The prescriptive strategy requires abandoning several positions that currently absorb political
      energy without producing strategic return. The broad-spectrum manufacturing-revival fantasy —
      that South Africa can rebuild its 1980s industrial base across every sector — has to be let
      go; focus is not the same as surrender. Import-substitution nostalgia, which produced the
      tariff walls of the apartheid era and the inefficiencies they protected, must be distinguished
      from sectoral-targeting strategies aimed at endowment-aligned activity. The pretence that
      state-owned enterprises can be simultaneously commercial and welfare instruments has to end;
      they are one or the other, and the conflation is the mechanism by which both functions
      deteriorate.
    </p>

    <h3 class="font-heading text-lg font-bold text-text-primary mb-2 mt-6">
      Internal Risks to Flag
    </h3>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The biggest internal risks are specific. The Government of National Unity coalition is
      unstable and its durability determines the reform horizon. Patronage networks inside the
      governing bloc resist SOE reform because SOE reform threatens their revenue streams, and the
      confrontation is political rather than merely administrative. The inequality-growth tension
      produces constant pressure for redistribution in excess of what the productive base can
      sustain. None of these risks is unique to South Africa; all have to be named as part of a
      strategy that proposes to act against them. A grand strategy that ignores the politics of its
      own implementation is a document, not a plan.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 9: Gap & Synthesis -->
  <section id="synthesis" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Gap and synthesis">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 9</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      Bridging the Gap: From Constitutional Non-Alignment to Endowment-Aligned Execution
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The argument of the previous sections reaches a specific synthesis: the current strategy's
      architecture is not wrong. Its Ends — the vision, the four national interests, the eight NSS
      pillars — and its Ways — active non-alignment, Pan-African agency, Ubuntu values-based
      entrepreneurship, coordinated multi-alignment — together form a broadly coherent doctrinal
      package. The values framework does real work, and the strategic discipline of reading security
      through the constitutional values of dignity, equality, and freedom distinguishes South Africa
      from most peer states. The problem is not doctrinal. It is a failure of economic foundation
      and execution priority.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Three bridging moves are required to convert the strategy from aspiration into plan.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">First, reprioritise the economic-security pillar as first
      among equals.</strong> The NSS formally presents eight co-equal pillars. That formal symmetry
      is analytically incorrect. Economic Security is not one of eight; it is the enabling condition
      for the other seven. Without sustained three-to-five-per-cent GDP growth, the fiscal base does
      not support the military pillar, the cyber pillar, the environmental pillar, or the cultural
      pillar. The doctrine should name this explicitly. The cost of the current framing — eight
      co-equal pillars — is that capital is allocated by precedent rather than by causal priority.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Second, ground diplomatic posture in commercial outcomes.</strong>
      The SAIIA recommendation to convert the Global South's numerical strength into agenda-setting
      power through technical expertise applies equally to the bilateral axis. Foreign policy should
      be measured, at the end of every fiscal year, by trade secured, foreign direct investment
      attracted, and technology transfer consummated — not by the volume of multilateral communiqué
      language. This is not a demotion of the values framework; it is a restatement of the premise
      that the values framework is funded by commerce.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      <strong class="text-text-primary">Third, accept strategic triage on defence.</strong> The
      SANDF cannot become, over any reasonable horizon, the force that the "Journey to Greatness"
      document describes. A fifteen-year roadmap to a modest but functional force — Special
      Operations capability, intelligence-surveillance-reconnaissance capability, and maritime-
      domain-awareness capability — is achievable. A paper plan for a force the fiscus cannot fund
      is not. The honest doctrine names the scope of the force that can be afforded and frees the
      fiscal space for the economic-security pillar on which every future force rests.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The dominant probable trajectory, as Otto and Nagar's scenario work and the Belfer Center and
      ISS analyses all converge in projecting, is sustained normative posture with incremental
      adaptation to external pressure and continued drift between stated and executable capability.
      The strategy persists in its current form because each separate institution has an incentive
      to defend its own pillar, and no single institution has the authority to impose the triage the
      synthesis requires. That is itself a coordination-deficit outcome, and it is the one the
      Reform Agenda articulated across this site is designed to address.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary leading-relaxed">
      The key variable across every scenario is economic recovery. Without it, the grand strategy
      becomes performative — elegantly drafted, diplomatically decorated, and quietly unaffordable.
      With it, the architecture that the doctrinal stack already provides becomes materially
      fundable. The next section makes the bridge explicit: how the domestic reform programme that
      GovCompass has articulated across its five pillars is the execution layer on which a grand
      strategy of any kind — current or endowment-aligned — must stand.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Alignment Section -->
  <section id="alignment" class="mb-14 scroll-mt-24" aria-label="Alignment with the GovCompass Reform Agenda">
    <p class="font-heading text-xs font-semibold text-text-secondary uppercase tracking-wide mb-1">Section 10 — The Bridge</p>
    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-text-primary mb-4">
      Alignment with the GovCompass Reform Agenda
    </h2>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Grand strategy answers the question of what a state seeks and how it deploys its instruments.
      Domestic governance reform answers the question of whether the state can actually operate the
      instruments it claims. The two questions are inseparable. A state whose municipalities cannot
      supply clean water, whose provincial education departments cannot staff qualified subject
      advisors, and whose national departments cannot coordinate cross-cutting reform cannot execute
      a national security strategy — regardless of how elegantly drafted the doctrine is.
    </p>

    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      The Reform Agenda articulated across GovCompass is the domestic execution layer. Every pillar
      of the Agenda corresponds to a pillar, Way, Mean, or risk family of the grand strategy. The
      correspondences are not coincidental. They are structural — the Agenda was designed around the
      RAARICLE™ diagnostic framework that isolates exactly the governance-design failures which
      erode the instruments of national power. The table below makes the mapping explicit.
    </p>

